WEBVTT

00:00:03.660 --> 00:00:06.040
Good afternoon.

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:07.000
My name is Christy Wyatt.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:09.940
I'm the director of Worldwide
Developer Relations.

00:00:10.010 --> 00:00:14.580
And we're here to talk about go-to-market
strategies and services for developers.

00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:19.120
Now, if you're an engineer here looking
for any technical content whatsoever,

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:22.440
this is the advanced warning
that you should leave,

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:27.560
because there is zero technical
content in this session whatsoever.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:29.720
This is a little bit of an experiment,
actually.

00:00:29.750 --> 00:00:34.010
We get asked a lot of times why we
talk-- why we don't talk to developers

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:37.550
at developer conference about how
they take the solutions they've

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:39.480
worked so hard to build to market.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:42.280
And maybe somebody is new
to the Apple community.

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:46.360
Maybe they are new to selling software,
period, and they've never actually had to

00:00:46.450 --> 00:00:48.190
take a product to market before.

00:00:48.370 --> 00:00:52.040
So we get a lot of questions
in developer relations.

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:54.760
And we thought that we would do a
little trial this year and put in a

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:58.660
session on the grid to see if this was
the sort of content that developers

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:00.500
at this event might want to hear.

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:03.750
Thank you.

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:11.340
I believe in ending on a high note,
so thank you all for coming.

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:13.620
These are some of the questions
we get asked all the time.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:17.100
My team specifically is responsible
for seeking out new partners and

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:20.120
taking partners to market and working
with partners on an ongoing basis.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:22.940
So these are the questions that
we get asked every single day.

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:26.700
These are the questions that come into
our developer program every single day.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:29.600
So we're going to go through the
top ten questions we get about

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:31.420
sales and marketing all the time.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:33.410
If you've been selling
products for a while,

00:01:33.410 --> 00:01:35.440
some of them may feel
a little rudimentary,

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:37.590
but maybe there's a few things
that are Apple unique that

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:38.920
you may learn this afternoon.

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:42.920
The first question is what are the
key components of a go-to-market plan?

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:45.910
If you've never actually had to
sell a piece of software before

00:01:46.050 --> 00:01:49.060
or try to sell a product before,
all the different things you need

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:51.800
to do to launch a product might
be just a little bit overwhelming.

00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:55.110
So the things that we're going to focus
most specifically on this afternoon

00:01:55.110 --> 00:01:56.720
are around marketing and sales.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.380
What are some easy ways or some
not-so-easy ways to market your product,

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:04.140
and what are the different options
for taking that product to market?

00:02:04.140 --> 00:02:06.760
Retail, online, channels, direct,
and so forth.

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:09.720
So starting off with marketing,
let's talk about marketing.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:13.020
We get asked a lot how to best do PR.

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:15.360
Should I be doing PR because
I'm a small organization?

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:16.820
Does it really make sense for me?

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:18.160
Is it going to cost me a lot of money?

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:21.020
PR, in fact,
could be probably one of the cheapest

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:24.890
forms of marketing and one of the
most effective if you do it right.

00:02:24.930 --> 00:02:27.930
Press releases don't cost a lot
to write or don't cost a lot to

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:31.060
get out there and get posted,
but you have to think very clearly

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:33.130
about what it is that you're doing.

00:02:33.140 --> 00:02:35.480
The first thing you have to
understand is who's your customer

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:37.780
and who are you trying to get
to and who do they listen to?

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:39.530
So what are the publications?

00:02:39.740 --> 00:02:40.690
What are the pages you're targeting?

00:02:40.770 --> 00:02:41.940
Who are the influential journalists?

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:44.110
How do you identify the influencers?

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:46.820
And then creating a message that
is very clear about your product

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:48.340
and attractive to that market.

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:51.530
Now that sounds really, really simple,
but oftentimes it's not.

00:02:51.590 --> 00:02:54.200
We see a lot of press releases
coming through that aren't

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:55.650
quite that crisp and clear.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:58.540
So you have to think really clearly
about your value proposition.

00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:00.710
And then repeat, repeat, repeat.

00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:03.930
The trick is saying the same thing
over and over and over and over

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:07.740
again until everybody knows what your
product and your brand stands for.

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:08.940
So clear messaging.

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:10.340
Identify the influencers.

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:11.940
One other thing you might
want to think about,

00:03:11.940 --> 00:03:15.740
especially if you're just starting out,
is maybe getting some professional help.

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:17.730
And I don't mean medical
professional help.

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:20.050
Although if you've tried to
do this for a little while,

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:21.140
you might require it.

00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:24.040
But we mean there's a lot of
really good freelancers out there

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:27.140
that make themselves available
to smaller organizations.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:28.540
They're incredibly easy to find.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:31.400
There's a URL here for an
association that freelancers make

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:33.140
themselves available through.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:36.390
One thing we would recommend is find
somebody who really understands the

00:03:36.390 --> 00:03:38.140
customers you're trying to get to.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:41.630
This could be a freelance person
who's really good at talking

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:43.300
to enterprise publications.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:45.100
And you're a consumer-focused product.

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:46.380
That's probably not
going to work out really,

00:03:46.380 --> 00:03:46.900
really well.

00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:49.900
So try to find someone who understands
the market you're going after.

00:03:50.030 --> 00:03:53.390
And then try to get that
clear message and repeat,

00:03:53.390 --> 00:03:54.780
repeat, repeat.

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:57.700
We've listed a couple of
the Apple publications.

00:03:57.850 --> 00:03:59.740
Some things you might want to
think about are do you want

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:01.680
to talk to the Apple press,
the people who write

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:02.900
about Apple all the time?

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:06.490
Or do you want to talk to people
who are publications and journalists

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:08.700
who are in the vertical market
that you're trying to attract?

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:10.900
So, for example,
talking to the Apple publications

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:13.500
or talking to someone
specifically in the life sciences,

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:16.830
like bio-IT world,
if you're writing an application

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:18.790
that's scientific in nature.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:21.140
It's really easy, generally,
to find the journalist

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:22.300
that you want to target.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:24.900
If you go to any one of these
publications and do a search on Apple,

00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:27.500
you're going to see who writes
about Apple all the time.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:30.970
And now you know who it is you
need to get your stuff in front of.

00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:34.650
A question we get all the time is
how do you get Apple to endorse

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.200
one of your press releases?

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.830
And I'm just going to be really,
really honest, it's incredibly,

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:40.740
incredibly hard.

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:43.600
We're really,
really tough about press releases and

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:45.940
putting our name on third party things.

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:48.300
Very few get Apple quotes.

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:52.290
This event, for example, we had, I think,
18 at the very most and this is a huge,

00:04:52.310 --> 00:04:54.060
huge event.

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:56.420
Some of the things we look for is to
make sure that the press releases that

00:04:56.460 --> 00:04:59.540
we're reviewing are very product related.

00:04:59.540 --> 00:05:01.820
They're about your products,
your customers.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:04.760
We never announce other people's things.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:07.640
We may support you in doing that.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.160
That you're going to distribute
them on a major news wire.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:12.500
So if it's not going through
a major news service,

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:14.920
we won't even really consider it.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:18.040
And that it's identifiable to some
target market that we're looking at.

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.020
And I know that's not on this list.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:23.440
We're going to talk to a little bit more
on how to get things in front of us.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:25.320
But these are some things to think about.

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:27.620
And again, you know,
we're always excited to see

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:31.700
partners doing press releases
about Apple related software.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:34.000
We don't think that they all
necessarily need to be quoted by Apple.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:36.440
But these are some of the
things that we're looking for.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.380
Another thing to think about
is what are some major events?

00:05:39.470 --> 00:05:42.220
If there's a lot of Apple media
going on around a major Apple event,

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:44.560
that may or may not be a good
time for you to be talking about

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:45.880
your Apple related product.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.980
So what are the major Apple events?

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:50.500
I'll give you a hint.

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:52.100
This is one.

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:55.740
There's actually three that we
consider to be major Apple events.

00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:58.540
Apple Expo's in Paris this
year in September.

00:05:58.540 --> 00:05:59.500
Macworld Expo in San Francisco.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:00.500
Always in San Francisco.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:03.930
Big,
big event for us even though it's not

00:06:03.990 --> 00:06:07.500
an Apple specific and Apple only event.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:08.630
And then WWDC.

00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:12.860
Each one of these events is very unique
in how they work with third parties.

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:16.220
But oftentimes they'll make
demo opportunities available

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:17.960
or booth opportunities.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:19.400
There may be PR opportunities.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:21.410
So you should go to the specific
websites and look for what are

00:06:21.410 --> 00:06:24.720
the third party opportunities
around those different events.

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:26.720
Another thing you may want to
think about is what other events

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:28.680
is Apple participating in?

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:31.770
So for example,
if you're writing education software,

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:33.010
NECC is in two weeks.

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:36.260
It's really pretty simple to
figure out whether Apple's going

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:37.840
to be at an event in a big way.

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:39.740
You look at the exhibitors
list and if we're there,

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:42.400
chances are someone from
Apple's going to be around.

00:06:42.450 --> 00:06:44.560
If you already have a booth planned
and you're going to be showing

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:47.060
Apple product in your booth,
we'd actually love to know.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:50.570
We oftentimes sort of plot out what
kind of Apple solutions are going to be

00:06:50.570 --> 00:06:52.440
showing on the floor of any major event.

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:54.560
And if you're showing your product,
we'd love to know about it.

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.980
So we'll let you know how
to do that in a little bit.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:10:43.800
[Transcript missing]

00:10:44.920 --> 00:10:46.460
Other online marketing opportunities.

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.600
So not all the ways to market
with Apple are through Apple.

00:10:49.600 --> 00:10:51.600
So, for example,
VersionTracker is another

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:54.850
very well-trafficked site
for third-party products.

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:57.770
We get a lot of folks that are
looking at the VersionTracker page and

00:10:57.770 --> 00:10:58.930
then coming back and talking to us.

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:00.620
So I've put the URL for that up here.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.650
Other Apple.com sites.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:07.080
So we get asked a lot how you
get on different Apple pages.

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:09.420
So, for example,
sometimes we reference third-party

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:12.600
software on the server page or
on the ITPro page or on some of

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:14.470
the other creative markets pages.

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:18.530
The answer is get your products
into MPG and the Downloads Guide.

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:22.500
When we're looking for new solutions,
maybe things we've missed,

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:25.930
maybe new solutions in emerging markets,
that's where we go look.

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:28.870
You know, the MPG, as we said,
is the most comprehensive software guide.

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:31.610
And so when the teams that are
responsible for vertical markets

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:33.840
are looking for new content,
that's kind of where they go.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:35.340
So I would suggest you start there.

00:11:37.270 --> 00:11:40.190
Other online marketing opportunities,
sometimes banner ads.

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:45.390
Banner ads obviously are
not necessarily free,

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:47.370
so they're not as cost effective
as some of the other things

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:48.680
that we were talking about.

00:11:48.690 --> 00:11:50.400
But they can be equally effective.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:53.340
Some other things to think about are,
as I was saying before,

00:11:53.500 --> 00:11:55.090
try to identify the target site.

00:11:55.090 --> 00:11:58.000
Is it a Mac community you're
looking for or is it a vertical

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.580
community you're looking for?

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:03.500
So, does it make sense to post some sort
of banner ad on one of these very

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:07.890
Mac-specific URLs that we're listing
here or do you want to try to identify

00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:13.030
sites that are well trafficked for the
target customer you're going after?

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:15.860
The other thing to think about is
whether you're really just trying

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:18.400
to build awareness or whether you're
actually trying to capture people.

00:12:18.530 --> 00:12:20.960
And so are you just trying to
put your graphic or your logo

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:23.030
and get your message up there,
or when they click through,

00:12:23.030 --> 00:12:26.070
is there something specific
you want to do with them?

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:29.090
So then that kind of leads us to sales.

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:31.640
If somebody clicks through and they
want to buy something from you,

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:32.860
what is that call to action?

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:37.960
So I would have to say that by far the
biggest percentage of questions that

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:41.340
we get are around sales of products
and what is the most effective way to

00:12:41.410 --> 00:12:43.530
sell products out to the Mac customers.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:46.870
Obviously there's many different
paths to market depending on what your

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:48.690
solution is and who your customer is.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:53.320
There's direct, retail, online,
through resellers or influencers or VARs.

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:56.480
Direct we're not going to talk all
that much about this afternoon.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:58.810
If you're doing direct sales,
chances are you know

00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:00.080
who your customers are.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.200
It's probably one of the most
expensive ways to go and sell

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:06.190
your product because you have
full-time people going and doing it.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:10.880
We're going to spend most of our time
this afternoon talking about retail,

00:13:10.890 --> 00:13:12.670
online, and resellers.

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:17.330
So is retail right for me?

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:21.210
Apple, as a company,
might know something about retail.

00:13:21.240 --> 00:13:24.050
If you were in the keynote,
we definitely know how to make very

00:13:24.050 --> 00:13:27.700
cool demos about our retail team,
because you saw that in the keynote.

00:13:27.700 --> 00:13:30.140
But actually, we've gotten a lot of
attention for retail.

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:33.120
And so to talk a little bit
not just about Apple retail,

00:13:33.120 --> 00:13:37.070
but some things you might want to think
about in approaching retail in general,

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:39.090
I want to introduce Carl Smit.

00:13:39.220 --> 00:13:41.750
Carl is the Retail Merchandising
Manager for the Apple Store for

00:13:41.750 --> 00:13:44.440
software products,
and he's going to to talk a little

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:46.290
bit about retail strategies.

00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:52.060
Good afternoon.

00:13:52.230 --> 00:13:57.500
So I'm the Product Merchandising
Manager for software in

00:13:57.500 --> 00:13:58.600
the Apple retail store.

00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:00.980
So all the software products.

00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:01.880
We have a few merchants.

00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:04.250
We have a different one for hardware.

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:09.350
And then we have some for overseas,
but we all work pretty

00:14:09.830 --> 00:14:12.230
closely together as a team.

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:15.680
What I'm going to start with is
just weighing the cost versus

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:15.680
the benefits of entering retail

00:14:16.100 --> 00:17:06.900
